Salamanders {
; Setemkia FallingTree
;
; This may very well be a finished image.  I'm not sure.
; Feedback and tweaks are welcome.  This picture may be
; too busy.  Any thoughts?
;
; A family of salamanders hiding in a dense forest.
; There are leaves in foreground and background.  The
; result is that the salamanders are difficult to see
; as is often the case in Nature.
;
; This is the first picture where I had a definate idea
; in mind before starting.  As oft happens, the result
; bears little resemblance to the original idea.
;
; I had seen a hollow julia image whose interior space
; resembled a salamander.  I thought I saved the
; parameters, but when I went looking for it I could not
; be found.  I played with what I had and stopped when
; I noticed that the spirals appeared to be composed
; of leaf shaped regions.  This resulted in over an hour
; playing with a color gradient.  Random gradients weren't
; working.  Eventually, I had to place color ranges by
; hand watching how the leaves filled in.  Leafy forrest
; in hand I went looking for my salamanders.  I never did
; find the region that sprompted this picture, but I did
; find something I liked.  I could say I colored the
; salamanders red as Fire Elementals (fire beings) are
; known as salamanders in ancient lore (perhaps because
; the protective slime of some species of this amphibian can
; cause viscious chemical burns).  However, the truth is,
; only the red range made them visible at all.  The final
; task was finding a way to duplicate the forrest layer on
; top so the salamanders would be partially hidden by the
; leaves as well as among them.
;
fractal:
  title="Salamanders" width=680 height=510 author="Setemkia FallingTree"
  created="August 1, 2001" numlayers=5
layer:
  method=linear caption="Foreground" opacity=100 visible=yes alpha=yes
  mergemode=hardlight
mapping:
  center=0.145423255236770976/0.4791463552871872 magn=478.654614893208064
  angle=270.000000683245344
formula:
  filename="fractint.ufm" entry="mandphoenixclx" maxiter=400
  percheck=normal p_p1=-0.001/1E-6 p_p2=0.5/0.01 p_degree=1 p_test="and"
  p_bailout=4
inside:
  transfer=none repeat=yes
outside:
  filename="dmj.ucl" entry="dmj-Distance" density=4 transfer=log repeat=yes
  p_power=3
gradient:
